    <statement><p>Find the <m>y</m>-intercept and any <m>x</m>-intercept(s) of the quadratic curve.</p>
<p><m>{y}={19x-21-4x^{2}}</m></p>
<p><m>y</m>-intercept: <fillin characters="16" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
<p><m>x</m>-intercept(s): <fillin characters="17" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(0,-21\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(1.75,0\right), \left(3,0\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>We need to change the parabola to standard form first:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {y} = {-4x^{2}+19x-21} }</m></p>
<p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>x=0</m> into <m>{y}={-4x^{2}+19x-21}</m>, and we have <m>y=-21</m>.</p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,-21)</m>.</p>
<p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>y=0</m> into <m>{y}={-4x^{2}+19x-21}</m>, and then solve for <m>x</m>.</p>
<p>For this problem, once we factor out the leading negative one, notice that the polynomial can be factored:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
   y \amp = {-4x^{2}+19x-21} \\
   0 \amp = {-4x^{2}+19x-21} \\
   0 \amp = -({4x^{2}-19x+21}) \\
   0 \amp = -(4x - 7)(x-3) \\
   4x - 7 = 0     \quad \amp \text{or} \quad x-3 = 0 \\
   4x      = 7 \quad \amp \text{or} \quad x = 3 \\
   x          = 1.75 \quad \amp \text{or} \quad x = 3
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercepts are <m>(1.75,0)</m> and <m>(3,0)</m>.</p>
</solution>
